    <button class="collapsible">What do I want to do at Brown?</button>
    <div class="content">

        <h5 style="font-weight: bold; text-align: center;">If admitted, here is what I would take and why I would take it.</h5>
        <p style="text-align: center;">This is meant to provide some more information about why I'm interested in Brown's program specifically.</p>

        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Introduction to Computer Graphics (1230), Advanced Computer Graphics (2240)</h6>
        <p>These are easily the classes I'd be most excited for. I've read some of Daniel Ritchie's research on 3D object generation and found the parts I understood 
            to be super interesting, and would love to take a class from him. It's also been a childhood dream of 
            mine to make a 3D game from scratch at some point in my career, and I think these two courses would provide a great foundation for that. 
            I'd be most excited about the raytracing part of 1230.</p>


        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Operating Systems (1670)</h6>
        <p>Though I took an OS class during undergrad and did well, I want to revisit these concepts because I feel that this topic is one of the most 
                underappreciated yet highly useful in the field of software engineering. I've also noticed that C is like the latin of programming languages, since many are based on it and 
                draw their syntactical ideas from it. Sharpening my C skills seems like a good idea for this reason.</p>

        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Probabilistic Methods in Computer Science (2540)</h6>
        <p>In the last year I've placed a heavier emphasis on machine learning and its statistical underpinnings, because 
            I'm well aware of how important it will become given the current climate. Since foundations are extremely 
            important, I believe this class would be very beneficial for me.
        </p>
               

        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Deep learning (2470)</h6>
        <p>This course would solidify a lot of ML concepts that I lack a thorough understanding of yet have used
             in projects before, like optimizers and the different types of neural networks that came before the transformer model.</p>

        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Computer Vision (1430)</h6>
        <p>I've had a lot of ideas in the past for projects that use computer vision in some form or another, 
            and this course would undoubtedly lay the proper groundwork for me to get started. I also just wanted to explore more avenues of machine learning 
        in general, and computer vision seems to be the most interesting.</p>

        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Design and Analysis of Algorithms (1570)</h6>
        <p>I've never taken a formal algorithms class, and although I've been on the leetcode grind and done a fair amount of competitive programming,
            I've still got some major flaws in my knowledge and approach to some problems. If I want to crush interviews and perform better in competitions,
            this course would definitely put me on the right path.
        </p>

        <h6 style="font-weight: bold;">Theory of Computation (1010)</h6>
        <p>This class was actually not required for my undergraduate CS degree, but a lot of the theory of computation 
            concepts I learned in discrete math I found very intriguing, so I would like to have this under my belt if I wish to call 
            myself an expert in computer science.</p>

    </div>


